         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">25, WILTON PLACE. S.W. ¶ London ¶ July 11 /73 ¶ My dear Sir ¶  ¶ I have now finished the Monocotyledons with inferior ovary and your specimens are packed up and will be sent off in a day or two I trus...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">73.07.11</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M3, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg rend="form%20text" style="color: #2f5496; font-family: Times; ">25, WILTON PLACE. S.W.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">London</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">July 11 /73</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have now finished the Monocotyledons with inferior ovary and your specimens are packed up and will be sent off in a day or two I trust you will receive them all safe.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In the box of <name key="Orchideae">Orchideae</name> which I returned I believe before I received the last sheet of your Fragmenta I may have left your <name key="Dendrobium%20bicuphum">Dendrobium bicuphum</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">dicuphum</seg>?</p>
               </note> under the name of D bigibbum I had described it under the latter name and although I afterwards perceived it was different from this Bot. Mag. plant I had not yet revised the genus finally and forgot to alter the name.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>i.e. on the returned herbarium sheet. <seg style="font-style: italic; ">D. dicuphum</seg> is included as a separate species in Bentham (1863-78), vol. 6, p. 277.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The box per Somersetshire arrived safe — the <name key="Scitamineae">Scitamineae</name> were already in type, so I left the descriptions as I had drawn them up from your sheet of Fragmenta which I had received in time</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The sixth vol. is now in print to the middle of <name key="Orchideae">Orchideae</name> — there had been some delay at Whitsuntide with the printers and they omitted to send me the clean sheets of what is printed off in time for the mail so I must send them by next mail</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Dioscorea%20lucida">Dioscorea lucida</name> Br. is evidently a Roxburghia and apparently identical with R. javanica Miq.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In Bentham (1863-78), vol. 7, p. 1, <seg style="font-style: italic; ">R. javanica</seg> is attributed to Kunth.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Brown's <name key="Calostemma%20alba">Calostemma alba</name>,<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">C. album</seg>?</p>
               </note> and <name key="Conostylis%20breviscapa">Conostylis breviscapa</name> are both very distinct species — the former I have seen nowhere else, the latter only from Baxter's collection<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>William Baxter <seg style="font-style: italic; ">fl</seg>. 1820s-1830s.</p>
               </note> besides Brown's <name key="Hypoxis%20marginata">Hypoxis marginata</name> is also only among Brown's<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The species mentioned are described in R. Brown (1810), pp. 298, 310 and 289 respectively.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Campynema">Campynema</name> must go as an exceptionaly hexandrous genus of <name key="Irideae">Irideae</name> of which it has the characteristic centrifugal inflorescence extrorse anthers and divided style — none of them occurring in <name key="Amaryllideae">Amaryllideae</name> of which <name key="Hypoxideae">Hypoxideae</name> are surely no more than a tribe.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am afraid you will not agree with me in many of my generic and other circumscriptions, but in these matters there is no positive test and every one acts according to his own convictions</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Your box exactly held the remainder of the Monocotyledons with inferior ovary. There remain <name key="Calectasia">Calectasia</name> &amp; <name key="Kingia">Kingia</name> which I presume you sent by mistake as there is much to come before them. However I hope that all will come in to the 7th vol. which will close the work if I live to work it out</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Yours very sincerely</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>George Bentham</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Baron Mueller</p>
